headline.main: TODD BACK HOME:A SAINT BRIDGES TWO WORLDS

results.lead_paragraph: MOBILE, Ala. In the flat Southland he calls home, Richard Todd is the aw- shucks, want-a-beer?-type whose friends and neighbors smile and say, ''Hi, Richard,'' when they see him. At Olan's Golden Rule Bar- B-Que (homemade chili, $1.65), there is a picture of him in the crimson-and- white uniform of the University of Alabama, and another of him in a Jet uniform. He owns 25 percent of the restaurant, so it isn't surprising that there are autographed pictures of him at the cashier's area saying, ''The sandwiches are great.'' Near the door is a poster of him throwing a football under a Jets' logo, with the New York City skyline as the backdrop.

headline.kicker: GEORGE M. LOW IS DEAD AT 58

results.snippet: George M. Low, president of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, who was a driving force in the Apollo moon landing program, died of cancer yesterday in Troy, N.Y. He was 58 years old.   Mr. Low had been ill for months, suffering from recurrent...
results.lead_paragraph: George M. Low, president of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, who was a driving force in the Apollo moon landing program, died of cancer yesterday in Troy, N.Y. He was 58 years old. Mr. Low had been ill for months, suffering from recurrent melanoma. On Monday the White House announced that he would be awarded the President's Medal of Freedom for his contributions to education and the nation's space program. In his 27 years with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration and its predecessor, the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics, Mr. Low served as an engineer and manager in the Mercury and Gemini programs and was put in charge of redesigning the Apollo spacecraft after a fire on the launching pad killed three astronauts in 1967.

headline.main: OFFBEAT MUSIC, SUN RA ARKESTRA TO GALLIC ROCK

results.snippet: Concertgoers in New York can get complacent.  Content that the city is the center of the cultural universe, they assume that sooner or later there will be a second chance to hear just about any musical event. This weekend, however, will bring three...
results.lead_paragraph: Concertgoers in New York can get complacent. Content that the city is the center of the cultural universe, they assume that sooner or later there will be a second chance to hear just about any musical event. This weekend, however, will bring three concerts that aren't likely to be repeated soon, even in New York. The pianist and bandleader Sun Ra, who says he was born on Saturn, will assemble a 100-member Arkestra for the first time in a decade; the reclusive New Orleans keyboardist, songwriter and producer Allen Toussaint will play his first full-length New York concerts since the mid-1970's and the French folk-rock group Malicorne, formed in 1973, will play its first American concert.

headline.main: RUSSIAN ASTRONAUT BECOMES FIRST WOMAN TO WALK IN SPACE

results.snippet: A Russian astronaut, Svetlana Savitskaya, became the first woman to walk in space today, the Tass press agency reported.     Miss Savitskaya, who is 36 years old, performed welding and soldering operations in the course of her historic excursion...
results.lead_paragraph: A Russian astronaut, Svetlana Savitskaya, became the first woman to walk in space today, the Tass press agency reported. Miss Savitskaya, who is 36 years old, performed welding and soldering operations in the course of her historic excursion in space, which lasted 3 hours and 35 minutes, Tass said. Her walk today upstages a planned space walk in October by an American woman, Kathryn D. Sullivan. Dr. Sullivan and another astronaut, David C. Leetsma, are to venture outside the space shuttle Challenger to demonstrate techniques for orbital refueling. That flight is scheduled for October.

results.snippet: Svetlana Savitskaya , a Russian astronaut, rocketed to fame of sorts last week by becoming the first woman to walk in space.
